## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2020 Universal Health Services ransomware attack** — which I first mentioned on Day 3 but want to revisit through the specific lens of risk tolerance.

UHS is one of the largest hospital networks in the United States. The ransomware attack took down IT systems across hundreds of facilities simultaneously, forcing staff to use paper records for over a week. The recovery cost was estimated at approximately $67 million.

Post-incident reporting indicated that UHS had known about vulnerabilities in its environment that could have been addressed before the attack. The decision not to prioritize those remediations was in effect a risk acceptance decision — but one that was never formally made, documented, or reviewed at the appropriate level of organizational authority.

That is the difference between implicit risk acceptance and a genuine risk management strategy. A documented risk tolerance framework would have required someone to formally evaluate whether the known vulnerabilities fell within acceptable thresholds, and if not, to activate a remediation process. Instead, the risks accumulated in an organizational blind spot — not formally accepted, not formally mitigated, just existing.

The $67 million recovery cost and the disruption to patient care across hundreds of facilities was the consequence of that gap. A risk management strategy does not guarantee you will never be breached. But it does mean that your most significant risks are visible, evaluated, and owned by someone with the authority to act on them.

