## The Challenge of "Zero Tolerance"

I want to address something that came up in today's exercise. The phrase "zero tolerance" gets used a lot in risk statements — and I used it myself in the draft above. But I am starting to think it needs to be handled carefully.

In a strict sense, zero tolerance for any risk means zero operation — because all systems carry some residual risk. What organizations usually mean when they say zero tolerance is something more specific: that certain categories of risk are so serious that they will not be accepted at any level as a permanent state, and that any instance of the risk will trigger an immediate and mandatory response.

That is a useful commitment — but it needs to be coupled with the resources and processes to actually follow through. A zero tolerance statement that is not backed by a functioning incident response process is not a risk management strategy. It is a statement of aspiration that will be quietly abandoned the first time following through is inconvenient.

I want to make sure the risk tolerance framework I develop for this project is honest about what zero tolerance actually means in operational terms — and backed by the processes that make it real.

